snippet.textDisplay: 2 stroke Detroit’s don’t burn oil. Detroit’s are notorious for being leaky engines that’s where the oil went. The 2 stroke just means the piston only has 2 strokes per cycle. Also I think yours might have a blower instead of a turbo because on a Detroit  there are no intake valves only exhaust. The air gets into the cylinder through holes at the bottom of the cylinder. The blower shoves air through the bottom of the cylinder. Our shop does Detroit’s all the time but I remember they were a little confusing when I first started. Love y’alls interesting projects and I hope this helped a little if you need to know any more just message me on insta @ross_t10

snippet.textDisplay: You didn't read my comment on your first video of this rebuild.  You are both reckless and dangerous to work around.  I saw probably a dozen major safety issues in this video that could have got one or both of you killed.    If one of the hydraulic lines break while your riding the forks up to the top, that boom goes into free fall and your dead.   Then you use the forklift to raise the semi tractor and hold it up so you can change the oil..... that's just playing Russian Roulette.   The big round things that lift the boom are called rams.  Some are designed to be rebuilt while others aren't but can be with the right equipment.    I would highly recommend that you have a reputable company rebuild the rams.  You do not have the tools or equipment needed to properly rebuild any of the big rams.

Some are designed to be rebuilt while others aren't but can be with the right equipment.    I would highly recommend that you have a reputable company rebuild the rams.  You do not have the tools or equipment needed to properly rebuild any of the big rams.
